1.body: Several projects involve writing a program to assist the user in creating a character for a tabletop roleplaying game (TTRPG). This game will be similar to Dungeons and Dragons Fifth Edition (D&D 5e), but many of the rules will be omitted or simplifed. Dungeons and Dragons is a tabletop roleplaying game . Even if you haven't played a TTRPG before, you've probably heard the name "Dungeons and Dragons" at some point. This assignment will use a modified version of some character creation rules from D&D 5e. The real rules can be found in the 5e System Reference Document (SRD), which you can read if you're curious and want to learn more. However, you do not need to read the SRD for this assignment. Below is a summary of some terms that will come up in this assignment: A player is a real person playing the game, and their character or player character ( pc for short) is the fictional character they control within the game. A character's class is the role they fill in the game's world. In a game like D&D, which focuses on fighting fantasy monsters, a character's class tells us their role in combat. A wizard casts spells, a rogue sneaks up on enemies, and a fighter... fights. Yes, everyone fights, but the fighter fights more directly, like with a sword and shield. A character's ancestry or race (the term varies by game, but I'll usually go with ancestry when not talking about a specific game) represents what kind of creature they are. Standard D&D races include elf, human, dwarf, goblin, gnome, halfling, and orc. However, depending on the game and who's running it, a TTRPG character could be anything: a ghost, a dragon, a talking bear, or a mannequin. I have run a game of D&D that included both a talking bear and a mannequin. The mannequin also talked, not just the bear. A character's HP or hit points represent how difficult they are to defeat in combat. A character's AC or armor class represents how hard they are to hit with an attack. A high AC may mean that a character is very good at avoiding attacks, or that a character is wearing armor that blocks most attacks. A character's ability scores are numbers that represent a character's strength, cunning, speed, and other qualities that affect most of their actions in the game. A character's ability modifiers are bonuses or penalties derived from their ability scores. The modifiers are the numbers we actually use in most calculations, and the scores only exist to determine the modifiers. At this point, you may be wondering why we bother with ability scores if we don't use them after calculating the modifiers. That's an excellent question! A character's level represents how powerful and experienced they are. In most RPGs, characters gain experience and level up to represent how they've grown during their adventures. In addition to standard six-sided dice (referred to as D6 dice), D&D uses several less common dice shapes: D4, D8, D10, D12, and D20.

2.body: Several projects involve writing a dice game similar to Yahtzee that can be played on the terminal. Yahtzee is a dice game played with five six-sided dice. The game has thirteen rounds, and in each round a player may roll their dice up to three times. After the first roll, a player can choose to only reroll some of their dice, leaving the others the same. Once a player is finished rolling their dice, they choose one of the thirteen scoring categories and receive points based on their dice. Each category can only be selected once. Before you begin the dice game projects, read the Yahtzee rules and play a few games so you understand how it works. The official rules are available from Hasbro, and the Wikipedia article also explains how to play. Project directions will assume you already understand how to play Yahtzee and how the scoring works.

This program must meet the following I/O requirements: The program accepts the required input in the order shown in the assignment and does not expect any additional input. The program produces each line of required output in the order specified in the assignment. The program may include additional output before, between, and after lines of required output. This additional output must be on a separate line from any required output. Your program must accept the following user input: The player's name (String) The character's name (String) The character's ancestry (String) The character's class (String) The character's level (int) The character's ability scores Strength (int) Dexterity (int) Constitution (int) If all user input is valid, then your program must print the following output: Player: <NAME> Character: <NAME>, level <LEVEL> <ANCESTRY> <CLASS> HP: <HP>, AC: <AC> Ability Scores: Str <STRENGTH SCORE> <STRENGTH MODIFIER> Dex <DEXTERITY SCORE> <DEXTERITY MODIFIER> Con <CONSTITUTION SCORE> <CONSTITUTION MODIFIER> Attacks: <ATTACK1 NAME> <ATTACK1 MODIFIER> <ATTACK2 NAME> <ATTACK2 MODIFIER> (note: some characters only have one attack) Two additional requirements: If a score (strength, dexterity, and constitution) is a single-digit number, then it must be padded with an extra space so that all scores are right-aligned in their column. Each modifier (strength, dexterity, constitution, and attack) must be preceded by a plus or minus sign. Negative modifiers have a minus sign, and nonnegative (which includes zero) modifiers have a plus sign. This reinforces how these numbers are meant to be used: they are usually added to dice rolls and other values rather than used on their own. The ability scores and attacks should also be indented for readability, but indentation will not be checked by the tests. 21.body: There are two ways for the user to enter invalid input: The user can enter a string or double when you were expecting an integer. If the user entered the word "nine" or the number 12.4 when asked for their level, then this would be the wrong type of input. The user can enter the correct type of input, but not one of the values they were allowed to enter. If the user entered -2 or 50 when asked for their level, then this would be the correct type of input (an integer), but not one of the integers they were allowed to choose for their level (a number from 1 to 20). The first kind of error is more complicated to deal with, and you won't learn how to handle those errors until later in the semester. You only need to worry about the second kind of error in this assignment. You can assume that the user will always enter the correct type of value, but your code must check whether it was one of the values they were allowed to choose. If the user enters an invalid value of the correct type, then your program must print the message ERROR: INVALID INPUT and exit. Here are all of the rules you must enforce when checking the user's input: The level must be an integer from 1 to 20. Each ability score must be an integer from 8 to 15. The ancestry must be either "human", "elf", or "dwarf". The class must be either "fighter", "ranger", or "rogue". You can assume that the user's input for class and ancestry are always lowercase. Your code must correctly handle the lowercase versions of these strings, but it doesn't matter what you do when given other capitalizations (such as "Human", "RANGER", or "DwARf"). The ancestry and class must also appear as all lowercase in the program's output .

22.body: This program involves more calculations and variables than the previous program. This section will serve as a reference for all values that are calculated by the program. Before any other calculations, some of the ability scores must be adjusted by the player's ancestry: If the character is a human, increase each ability score by one. If the character is an elf, increase their dexterity score by two. If the character is a dwarf, increase their constitution score by two. Each ability score has an associated number called its modifier . The modifier does not alter the score , it is derived from the score. The srd link has a table showing the modifier associated with each score from 1 to 30, but we can calculate the modifier with a formula. Each ability modifier is calculated by dividing the score by 2 and subtracting 5. The formula should look like this: modifier = score / 2 - 5. It's important that you divide before subtracting because integer division will round towards zero, not down. We could perform a similar calculation by subtracting 10 and then dividing by 2, but this would give the wrong value for odd ability scores below 10. For example, a score of 9 would produce a modifier of 0 when it should have a modifier of -1. The character's HP equals their level multiplied by the sum of their constitution modifier and their "hit die". The hit die is determined by the character's class. A fighter has a hit die of 10, and the other two classes have a hit die of 8. The formula should look like this: hp = level * (conModifier + hitDie). The character's AC (armor class) uses a different formula depending on their class: A fighter's AC is equal to 18 A ranger's AC is equal to 15 plus their dexterity modifier, but their AC cannot be higher than 17 A rogue's AC is equal to 12 plus their dexterity modifier The character's proficiency is not displayed, but it is used to determine their attack bonus. You can calculate proficiency with the formula proficiency = 1 + (level + 3) / 4. Depending on their class, the character has one or two attacks. Each attack has a name and a bonus. The bonus is equal to the character's proficiency bonus plus one of their ability modifiers. A fighter has one attack called Greatsword, which uses their strength modifier A rogue has two attacks: Dagger and Crossbow, which both use their dexterity modifier A ranger has two attacks: Longsword, which uses their strength modifier, and Longbow, which uses their dexterity modifier

32.body: To ensure compatibility with my tests, there are a few additional requirements whenever you have to generate a random number: Each random number is generated by either the roll function or the d6 function of the Dice class. Your program "rolls" the dice in the order they appear in the array. Your program does not roll extra dice. For example, calling one of the Dice class's functions to generate a random number when you don't need to roll a die, or rolling each die twice instead of once.
